T1  - Psychological distress in women with polycystic ovary syndrome: the role of attachment and coping.
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.1080/13548506.2020.1754436
A1  - Simon, Signe
A1  - Keitel, Merle
A1  - Bigony, Cara
A1  - Park-Taylor, Jennie
Y1  - 2021//
Y2  - 20200420//
N2  - Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), a chronic female endocrine disorder, is a leading cause of infertility and its symptoms tend to negatively affect appearance, physical health, and psychological well-being. Utilizing attachment theory as a theoretical framework, this study examined the relationships among anxious and avoidant attachment, hyperactivating and deactivating coping, and psychological distress in a sample of 183 women diagnosed with PCOS. Hierarchical multiple regression analyses revealed significant relationships among attachment, coping, and distress as well as mediation effects. Implications, limitations, and recommendations for future research are discussed.
