T1  - Testosterone in Women: Measurement and Therapeutic Use.
T3  - Comment in: J Obstet Gynaecol Can. 2017 Nov;39(11):976 PMID: 29080729 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/29080729] Comment in: J Obstet Gynaecol Can. 2017 Nov;39(11):977 PMID: 29080730 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/29080730]
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.jogc.2017.01.006
A1  - Kathryn Korkidakis, Ann
A1  - Reid, Robert L
Y1  - 2017//
N1  - Comment in (CIN)
N2  - Androgens, both in excessive and depleted states, have been implicated in female reproductive health disorders. As such, serum testosterone measurements are frequently ordered by physicians in cases of sexual dysfunction and in women presenting with hirsutism. Commercially available androgen assays have significant limitations in the female population. Furthermore, the measurements themselves are not always informative in patient diagnosis, treatment, or prognosis. This article reviews the limitations of serum androgen measurements in women suspected to have elevated or reduced androgen action. Finally, we consider when therapeutic use of androgen replacement may be appropriate for women with sexual interest/arousal disorders. Copyright © 2017 The Society of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists of Canada/La Societe des obstetriciens et gynecologues du Canada. Published by Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.
